{"id": "duc04-testb-32:19#57", "contents": "The government's investigation of Microsoft has spanned multiple administrations and involved numerous government lawyers and investigators. It has been a complex and evolving process, with no clear example of consistent public policy. The investigation began in 1989, when Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman, appeared at a news conference with a senior executive from IBM. The two companies were collaborating on a new operating system called OS/2, but Microsoft was also selling a competing product, Windows. The industry trade press was filled with worried articles about which system would become the new standard."}
